Here's the complete implementation:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Configure max request body size to allow up to 10MB uploads
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 10 * 1024 * 1024; // 10MB
});

builder.Services.AddAntiforgery();

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAntiforgery();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    if (file.Length == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No file provided.");

    if (file.Length > 10 * 1024 * 1024)
        return Results.BadRequest("File exceeds 10MB limit.");

    var allowedTypes = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png" };
    if (!allowedTypes.Contains(file.ContentType, StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are allowed.");

    var uploadsPath = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsPath);

    // Prevent path traversal and collisions
    var fileName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsPath, fileName);

    await using var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Create);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName });
})
.DisableAntiforgery(); // Remove this line if you want CSRF protection on the endpoint

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** — sets the max request body at the server level so oversized requests are rejected early.
- **Content-type check** — validates MIME type against an allowlist.
- **Safe filename** — uses a GUID to avoid path traversal and name collisions.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed if clients (e.g., mobile apps) won't send antiforgery tokens. Remove it to enforce CSRF protection (clients must then send the token via header/form field).

If you're behind IIS, also add to `web.config`:

```xml
<system.webServer>
  <security>
    <requestFiltering>
      <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="10485760" />
    </requestFiltering>
  </security>
</system.webServer>
```
